   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_IE">London</placeName>
                  <date when="1825-06-28"/>June 28. 25<lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>My friends in Town are<lb/>
               exclaiming at the deep scarlet hue in<lb/>
               my face with which I have <add>just</add> returned<lb/>
               from Margate - Some of them ascribe<lb/>
               it to the pony and donkey chaises<lb/>
               in which I have been wheeling about<lb/>
               with my little tribe - Some to two<lb/>
               days boat sailing with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WilsL1">Uncle Lestock</persName>
               <lb/>
               and my boys - and others insinuate<lb/>
               that Smuggled gin and Rhenish wine<lb/>
               are cheap on the Sea coast - But<lb/>
               they are all wide of the mark -<lb/>
               it is the inextinguishable blush<lb/>
               produced by accidentally cutting,<lb/>
               a few days ago only, the Second<lb/>
               leaf of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Early2">Harry and Lucy</title> - Al! my<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page02.jpg"/>
               
               dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> what misguiding imp<lb/>
               <lb/>
               could have instigated you to put<lb/>
               the children of such an unknown<lb/>
               person as I am <del>into</del> at the very<lb/>
               head and front of your book ! -<lb/>
               I know full well the full tide of<lb/>
               generous feeling that rushed into<lb/>
               your mind when the idea first <choice>
                  <orig>sug-<lb/>
               -gested</orig>
                  <reg>suggested</reg>
               </choice> itself to you - I know the<lb/>
               pleasure it gave you - and yet<lb/>
               I cannot help deploring it most<lb/>
               sincerely for your sake or rather for<lb/>
               the sake of the book itself. - <unclear>Besides</unclear>
               <lb/>
               which another evil will result - I<lb/>
               fear the effects on my self - finding<lb/>
               my name floating down to future fame<lb/>
               with your's I shall become as<lb/>
               insolent as the children <add>to whom it is dedicated.</add>
               <del>themselves</del>
               <lb/>
               - They indeed will desire benefit,<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page03.jpg"/>
               
               for if any thing on earth can stimulate<lb/>
               them to exertion it must be the<lb/>
               endeavor to render themselves worthy<lb/>
               of the honor you have conferred on<lb/>
               them, by following up some of the<lb/>
               avenues to Science which you have<lb/>
               so ably chalked out -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I long to hear from you<lb/>
               how you like the appearance<lb/>
               of the work now that it is all<lb/>
               before you - I long also to<lb/>
               hear but with some little<lb/>
               timouressness if there be such<lb/>
               a word how far you approve<lb/>
               of such parts as being within my<lb/>
               immediate knowledge - I dared to<lb/>
               <unclear>alter</unclear> - and with a still deeper<lb/>
               feeling than even timourousness how<lb/>
               you brook the curtailments which<lb/>
               were requisite to reduce the 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. vol. &amp; which<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page04.jpg"/>
               <add>though</add> you empowered me to make I may<lb/>
               not have made in the right places.<lb/>
               - Pray tell me your mind - next<lb/>
               <del>W</del> to the pleasure of having one's<lb/>
               actions approved is having <del>these</del>
               <add>one's</add>
               <lb/>
               faults pointed out - To be <choice>
                  <orig>judici-<lb/>
               -ously</orig>
                  <reg>judiciously</reg>
               </choice> scolded pleases me much<lb/>
               more than to be injudiciously praised.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>The first pages of all the volumes<lb/>
               look to me very blank without some<lb/>
               title - but the two first volumes<lb/>
               were so printed, and I supposed it<lb/>
               met with your approbation -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hunter</persName> has been very ill -<lb/>
               I called at his shop this afternoon<lb/>
                  and finding that he is at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Isle-of-Wight_ENK">Isle<lb/>
               of Wight</placeName> I did not choose to leave<lb/>
               your note for the edification of his<lb/>
               hopeful step-son <add>acts for him in his absence, and</add> who of course opens<lb/>
               his<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page05.jpg"/>
               
               his letters - I will forward it by post.<lb/>
               - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName>'s <unclear>directions</unclear> are conditional<lb/>
               if I approve of it - I cannot help<lb/>
               approving it - it contains <unclear>merely</unclear>
               <lb/>
               a repetition of what you before bound<lb/>
               yourself to do - and a repetition<lb/>
               of the honorable &amp; delicate feelings<lb/>
               which had <unclear>decided</unclear> your choice of<lb/>
               the title - and which you before<lb/>
               mentioned - Therefore it can do<lb/>
               no harm - it pledges you to nothing<lb/>
               new - and if <add>he</add> has half an ounce of feelings<lb/>
               it must justly sting them for having<lb/>
               said any thing further about the<lb/>
               change of title. That is punishment<lb/>
               enough for him - a little allowance<lb/>
               must be made for him - consider<lb/>
               he has a wife (with a ton of feelings)<lb/>
               whose constant opinion is that his<lb/>
               opinion is wrong - consider that his<lb/>
               only child has some deep seated<lb/>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page06.jpg"/>
               
               disease which has required a <choice>
                  <orig>consulta-<lb/>
               -tion</orig>
                  <reg>consultation</reg>
               </choice> - consider his stepson - and<lb/>
               consider the Hunts - and then<lb/>
               consider a little disappointment working<lb/>
               on all this - and I am sure you will<lb/>
               not be very angry -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I find a letter from him to<lb/>
                  me with a copy of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Frank1">Frank</title> requesting<lb/>
               me to correct inaccuracies &amp; - I<lb/>
               take it for granted that this has<lb/>
               been done by your command or<lb/>
               consent, and therefore I have or<lb/>
               rather shall write to him that as<lb/>
               soon as I receive your directions &amp;<lb/>
               corrections I will with pleasure<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">infuse</hi> them - <title ref="./Workography.xml#Frank1">Frank</title> is a<lb/>
               delightful book - and has but few<lb/>
               errors - and those you know<lb/>
            </p>
            <pb n="7" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page07.jpg"/>
            <p>So much for business - Now I have<lb/>
               to thank you for many little kindnesses<lb/>
               which were not unappreciated though<lb/>
                  unacknowledged - First for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet</persName>s dear<lb/>
                  &amp; amusing account of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RhodX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Rhodes</persName> &amp; his<lb/>
               <unclear>claims</unclear> which you found time to copy -<lb/>
               - Next I have to thank you for the<lb/>
               bundle of letters you sent - and which<lb/>
               I read as fast as I could find a spare<lb/>
               minute or two - I carried some of<lb/>
                  them as you desired to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollaH1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Holland</persName> -<lb/>
                  The most sensible among them all <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MorrX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                  Morritt</persName>'s to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StrickX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Strickland</persName> I did not<lb/>
               shew him - because they are probably<lb/>
               acquainted, and it might have come<lb/>
                     to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MorrX1">M</persName>'s knowledge that his letter <del>was</del> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StrickX1">S.</persName>
               <lb/>
                  was lent to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">E.</persName> &amp; by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">E.</persName> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">B</persName> - and By <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">B.</persName>
               <lb/>
                  to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollaH1">H.</persName> - and so on -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I have also to thank you for very<lb/>
               good advice about <del>my</del> not overworking<lb/>
               my sick boy - at a new school - but<lb/>
               <pb n="8" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page08.jpg"/>
               
               it was <unclear>
                  <hi rend="underline">tother</hi>
               </unclear> boy who went to the new<lb/>
                  school. - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauD2">D A B</persName> has not returned to<lb/>
               school yet nor <add>is</add> he likely to do so -<lb/>
               for I am very much grieved to say that<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BondX1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Bond</persName> died suddenly last week -<lb/>
               And we are yet ignorant who is to<lb/>
               succeed him, and consequently whether<lb/>
               we shall continue <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauD2">
                  <unclear>D A B</unclear>
               </persName> there or<lb/>
               again be obliged to school-hunt -<lb/>
                  - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">His mother</persName> wants me to send him<lb/>
                  to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ClemX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Clement</persName> of whom <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MareX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. <unclear>Marent</unclear>
               </persName> and<lb/>
               others speak in raptures <add>but he is 80 Guineas!</add> - I have 1/2<lb/>
                  a mind to try <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BellX1">the Bell ringing man<lb/>
                  at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Birmingham_ENK">Birmingham</placeName>
               </persName> about whom you and I<lb/>
               had some conversation and of whom<lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Janus1">the Edinburgh</title> speaks so warmly - but<lb/>
               there are I fear many good reasons<lb/>
               against it - besides <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauM1">Mamma</persName>'s dislike</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>You were right in supposing that<lb/>
               I would not sell your share in<lb/>
               the Manufactory <choice>
                  <abbr>Comp<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>.</abbr>
                  <reg>Company</reg>
               </choice> upon your<lb/>
               <pb n="9" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page09.jpg"/>
               
               first bidding. - I must inquire about<lb/>
               the form which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> must sign as they<lb/>
               are all in his name - Besides they<lb/>
               are now at a discount - I am really<lb/>
               vexed at having entangled my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH2">sister</persName> him<lb/>
               and you in this scrape and my poor<lb/>
               brother too who can still less afford to<lb/>
               lose by my awkward endeavors to put<lb/>
               money in his &amp; your pockets - But at<lb/>
               that time no one foresaw the panic<lb/>
               which seized the public or the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ScotJ1">Lord Chancellor</persName>s<lb/>
               speech and <add>which</add> depreciated all shares -<lb/>
               My plan was <del>that</del> to sell the majority<lb/>
               of the shares at a premium which would<lb/>
               pay one or two calls or deposits so that<lb/>
               you might hold the remainder for<lb/>
               nothing - Now I fear you will soon<lb/>
               have to pay £5 call on each of the<lb/>
               50 shares before they rise above par<lb/>
               So as to enable me to sell for you<lb/>
               without loss - Unless you all<lb/>
               choose to lose at once half your<lb/>
               deposit viz £25 to get rid of <unclear>the</unclear>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="10" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB901_1825_06_28_page10.jpg"/>
               
               business at once - Determine - Our<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">Act</hi>
               <add>of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Houses-of-Parliament_ENK">Parliament</placeName>
               </add> having received the Royal Assent we<lb/>
               are now going to work - - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RiceT1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Spring Rice</persName>
               <lb/>
               has been elected Chairman and I Deputy<lb/>
               Chairman - The former has very handsomely<lb/>
               accepted the Office - The latter has very<lb/>
               ungraciously refused it. - But my<lb/>
               refusal has not been accepted and<lb/>
               tomorrow they are to try to persuade<lb/>
               me -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I was in hopes that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Brinkley</persName>
               <lb/>
               would have to gone to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> this year<lb/>
               and that I might have followed in<lb/>
               his train, but he will not - and<lb/>
               I <unclear>verily</unclear> believe I must go in about<lb/>
               3 weeks !! - </p>
            <closer>Have you any command<lb/>
               there for your very very affectionate<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">F Beau</persName> -<lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>I cannot get any of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BartC1">Barton</persName>'s <del>ornamented</del> Iris clasps - Why<lb/>
               they do not make them I cannot discover<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>I cannot by any means find out whether <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HollaH1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Holland</persName>
                  <lb/>
               has any taste for engravings - but as he is going to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
                  <lb/>
               for <hi rend="underline">nine</hi> days perhaps you may see him<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <note>28 June 1825</note>
            <lb/>
         </div>
